      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The \"natural flow of ideas\" argument posits that the internet functions best as an unmediated public square where ideas compete freely, regardless of their quality or potential offense. Content moderation laws, even those framed as safety measures, are inherently selective interventions, meaning the state or platform decides which ideas are permissible. Age verification, while seemingly benign, functions as a gatekeeping mechanism that curtails access to information based on arbitrary bureaucratic criteria, thus disrupting the natural exchange of thought.",
      "source": "target",
